<h1>Problem 1011 - 2021 BMO2, P4 of 4, N</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 7</h2>
<p>Matthew writes down a sequence \(a_1,a_2,a_3,\ldots\) of positive integers. Each \(a_n\) is the smallest
positive integer, different from all previous terms in the sequence, such that the mean of the
terms \(a_1,a_2,\ldots,a_n\) is an integer. Prove that the sequence defined by \(a_i-i\) for \(i=1,2,3,\ldots\) contains every integer exactly once.</p>
